comment.author: 91812074@N06
comment.text: This is indeed the family crest of the Ords, whose family history is detailed here (ordfamilies.suttoncoldfieldatoz.com/D.html). Thanks to the clue provided by the self-identification with Lincoln's Inn, the specific John Ord we're dealing with here may be this one (histfam.familysearch.org/getperson.php?personID=I76310&am...) who in addition to being a barrister belonging to Lincoln's Inn was MP for Mitchell in Cornwall. Given the likelihood, I will update the tags with his information. Since his birth date is unclear, I have used the year of his christening, designated by the (c) in the tag.

comment.author: 58592597@N05
comment.text: It's also possible it might be this John Ord (1729?-1814), www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/20809/20807?docPos=4 His entry in Oxford DNB records his Lincolns Inn association. There is another bookplate (with same crest but different style) "John Ord 1761" but it's unclear if both bookplates belonged to the same John Ord (see here in English bookplates ....: books.google.com/books?id=INwYkTsw4csC&pg=PA96&lp... Also there exists an 1812 auction catalog entitled: A catalogue of a portion of the library of John Ord / [sold at auction by Leigh & Sotheby, 23 Apr. & 2 following days, 1812]. (no digital copy available at this time so I can't check for the title) but both the Folger and JCB libraries have identified the same "John Ord, 1729?-1814" as former owner for books with both of the above mentioned bookplates.

comment.author: 58880069@N07
comment.text: The early reader of the Penn copy of the Epigrams, probably a Roman Catholic, expunged the name of the humanist Erasmus of Rotterdam wherever it appeared in this copy. Because of Erasmus' refusal to abjure his loyalty to the Roman Catholic Church, he was seen by some Catholics as essentially not different from the Protestants.

comment.text: I defy any true bibliophile to look at this book for the first time on the Quays, as I did, without experiencing a very deep emotion. It is a collection, made toward the close of the XVth century, of a series of funeral orations and of discourses pronounced on the occasion of Embassies of obedience to several popes, the last of whom is Alexander VI. The appearance of this book bespeaks such orations as those of Carvajal, Almeida, Tilly [...] [...]. which constitute the very gems of an American library. The plaquettes were all printed in Rome by Plannck, Besicken and other printers dear to American collectors. The name of Antonius Geraldini, Columbus' friend is also to be found among its [...]s; and although every one of these plaquettes almost was printed with the types used for Columbus' epistoles, I [...] to to say that there is not one line or one word which refers to America. The orations are all valuable, but not to such a degree as Americana would be. Fancy! Had this collection been made three months later, there is an even chance that it would have been filled with plaquettes worth from two to three thousand francs a piece!!! H.H[arrisse] [Ms. note signed "H.H." (expanded in another hand to "H.H[arrsse]", i.e. Henry Harrisse) on front free endpaper. Harrisse (1823–1910) was a lawyer, bibliographer and historian who specialized in the European explorations of the Americas and the early history of the New World, hence his focus on Columbus and his printers in this note. Established form: Harrisse, Henry, 1829-1910]

comment.text: This is a very interesting one, as it consists of two apparently unrelated threads. The image is indeed of the Old East India House on Leadenhall Street in London, before the more famous one replaced it (and in turn itself was replaced, and today the famous Lloyd's of London Building stands on the site): commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Old_East_India_House.jpg The Boies Penrose we have here is likely one and the same with the cantankerous and very colorful 19th-early 20th century lawyer and Republican politician from our own city: en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boies_Penrose Established here in VIAF: viaf.org/viaf/75092475/ Why Mr. Penrose had the Old East India House depicted upon his bookplate is likely at this point a matter of speculation, the truth probably having gone to the grave with him.

comment.text: Duplicate stamp from the Bridgewater Library: "Duplicate Bridgew[ate]r Lib[rar]y". The Bridgewater Library was a family library, "the oldest large family collection in England to survive intact into modern times". The library was begun by Thomas Egerton, 1st Viscount Brackley at Tafton Park in Cheshire, and added to by his son John Egerton, 1st Earl of Bridgewater. John Egerton, 2nd Earl of Bridgewater also added to the library, and is said to have compiled a manuscript catalogue to it. The library now "forms the core of the Elizabethan and early Stuart collection at the Huntington Library". Bridgewater House Library

His stamp appears on the title page of this book, as well as a book label of The Adair Book Store of Chicago, Illinois on the front pastedown. comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Armorial bookplate of Sir Humphrey Francis de Trafford, 3rd Baronet (1862-1929). According to his obituary in The Times of London (11 January 1929; p. 14, issue 45098, col. C), he was "a great sportsman, taking an active part in hunting, shooting, polo, cricket, lawn tennis, and coursing, while he was not less interested in field trials for sporting dogs, agricultural and dog shows, and the breeding of horses, cattle, dogs and other animals." Though he inherited great wealth on his father's death in 1886, by the 1890s he had fallen into considerable debt and sold the family estate, Trafford Park, in 1896. In 1904 a special Act of Parliament was passed "to relieve him of his embarrassments" (op. cit.), but in 1907 he again faced bankruptcy. According to a contemporary account in The New York Times (28 July 1907: C1.), "When asked how he came to get through such a vast sum as $2,500,000 in eighteen years, Sir Humphrey admitted that he had lost large amounts in betting and had to have recourse to money lenders, to one of whom he paid 15 per cent. interest." Established heading: De Trafford, Humphrey F. (Humphrey Francis), Sir, 1862-1929

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Bookplate of Edmund McClure (d. 1922). He was editorial secretary of the Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge (SPCK) from 1875-1915. According to his obituary in The Times of London (20 November 1922; p. 5; issue 43193, col. B), "Throughout that long period he exercised a firm control over the great mass of publications issued by the society, and when he retired remarkable tributes were paid by leading churchmen to his zeal and ability." He also wrote several books on historical and religious topics. The phrase "Beatos puto quibus deorum munere datum est aut facere scribenda aut scribere legenda beatissimos vero quib[us] utru[m]que" comes from Pliny the Younger, epistle 6.16. Established heading: McClure, Edmund, d. 1922

comment.text: Title leaf of an early printed edition of Sallust's Bellum Jugurthinum (Leipzig: Martin Landsberg, after 1500), with ms. annotation. In this edition (BSB-Ink. S-25; IBP 4859), line 2 of title reads: "de Bello Iugurtino."; explicit of text (leaf G6r, line 24) reads: "C. Crispi Salustij de bello Iugurtino Finis." and is followed by Landsberg's device (cf. E. Weil, Deutschen Druckerzeichen des XV. Jahrhunderts, no. 71c). In another edition (GW M39666; VD 16 S 1397), line 2 of title reads: "de bello Iugurtino."; explicit of text (leaf G6r, lines 24-25) reads: "C. Crispi Salustij debello Iugurtino Finis. Per Baccalarium Martinum Herbipolensem." without device. Goff S-88, giving an imprint consistent with the latter edition, appears to conflate the two. Established heading: Sallust, 86-34 B.C.
